Notes: After my cursory analysis, it appears that increase the number of trees does have an impact on the predictive accuracy of the training dataset, but this severely compromises that of the testing dataset. In addition, increase the number of variables upon branching (mtry) seems to worsen predictive outcomes. Instead, reducing the variables (including some of those that we have originally listed given low MeanDecreaseAcc and MeanGiniCoef) increases the sample size, which appears to augment the predictive accuracy with ntree=500 and mtry=5 (default settings.) I cannot seem to get the partial plot to work because it does not like the categorical nature of my variables, so I will likely need help with that, but otherwise, it seems promising to have somewhat of a direction. Over the weekend (7/8-7/11), if time permits, I will try to resolve my concerns with the geospatial visualization of variables (if it is actually averaging per state or selecting the last entry per state.)
